Also known as [b]Inspector Zenigata[/b]

An Interpol detective who is absolutely determined to arrest [[Arsene Lupin III]] and his posse, but he's most obsessed with Lupin's capture over the others. title: art_deco
body:
A type of art style popular during the early 20th century, approximately from 1920 to 1940. It is characterized by an elegant, simplistic and uncluttered style composed of straight lines, sharp edges, and fully circular curves. The style of Art Deco must be seen in comparison to its predecessor, [[Art Nouveau]]. Whereas Art Nouveau used swirly, organic designs marked by elaborate details, Art Deco sought to remove any unnecessary details and create a clean, functionalistic design. However, the boundary between Art Nouveau and Art Deco can get hazy at times.

title: borscht_(food)
body:
A soup of Eastern-European origin, eaten in countries such as Ukraine, Russia, Poland, etc.
It gains its distinctive red color from the use of beetroots and it also contains many vegetables such as carrots, cabbages or potatoes and chunks of meat. It's most usually served with smetana/sour cream. 

Although its most known variant is red borscht, yellow, green and "white" variants exist, all under the same name. 

Commonly seen with Russian characters or [[kantai_collection|kanmusus]].

title: uh-60_blackhawk
body:
The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade, twin-engine, medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft. 

Named after the Native American war leader Black Hawk, the UH-60A entered service with the U.S. Army in 1979, to replace the Bell UH-1 Iroquois as the Army's tactical transport helicopter. This was followed by the fielding of electronic warfare and special operations variants of the Black Hawk. 

Modified versions have also been developed for the U.S. Navy, Air Force, and Coast Guard. In addition to U.S. Army use, the UH-60 family has been exported to several nations. Black Hawks have served in combat during conflicts in Grenada, Panama, Iraq, Somalia, the Balkans, Afghanistan, and other areas in the Middle East.

title: full_metal_jacket
body:
"[i]In Vietnam, the wind doesn't blow. It sucks.[/i]" Main tagline.

[b][i]Full Metal Jacket[/i][/b] is a 1987 British-American war film directed and produced by [[Stanley Kubrick]]. 

The screenplay by Kubrick, Michael Herr, and Gustav Hasford was based on Hasford's 1979 novel, [i]The Short-Timers[/i]. 

Its storyline follows a platoon of U.S. Marines through their training, primarily focusing on two privates, Joker and Pyle, who struggle to get through camp under their foul-mouthed drill instructor, [[sgt_hartman|Gunnery Sergeant Hartman]], and the experiences of two of the platoon's Marines in the Tet Offensive during the [[Vietnam War]]. The film's title refers to the full metal jacket bullet used by soldiers. 

Full Metal Jacket received critical acclaim and an Academy Award nomination for Best Adapted Screenplay for Kubrick, Herr, and Hasford. In 2001, the American Film Institute placed it at No. 95 in their "AFI's 100 Years...100 Thrills" poll.

title: upright_restraints
body:
Fixed [[restraints]] that keep the subject's body upright or vertical (or very nearly so). This includes suspension, sitting, and kneeling restraints, as long as the main part of the subject's body (and focus of the image) is [b]upright[/b], rather than lying down, leaning, bent over, etc. For that reason, this would almost never be applied to [[glory_wall]]s and similar where the subject is in a forced leaning position.

If the subject is also standing while restrained, add the [[standing_restraints]] tag as well.

If the character is upright, but the restraints aren't keeping them that way, that doesn't count as upright restraints. An example would be a character standing while their arms and legs are tied. Since they could lie down (or bend over), they aren't actually permanently restrained in the upright position.

title: standing_restraints
body:
Fixed [[restraints]] that keep the subject in a standing position (or nearly so). This [i]doesn't[/i] include restraints where the subject is upright but not standing, for instance when hanging, kneeling, sitting, or on a rotated slab. Use [[upright_restraints]] in these cases.

With restraints, the subject is often supported in some way, but to merit this tag they should have their feet on the ground and could theoretically be supporting their own weight if not for the restraints.

If the subject's feet can't be seen, but it can be reasonably inferred that they are standing, use this tag.

If the character is [[standing]], but the restraints aren't keeping them that way, that doesn't count as standing restraints. An example would be a character standing while their arms and legs are tied. Since they could sit down (or fall over), they aren't actually restrained to a standing position.

title: restraints
body:
A fixed, purposeful means to make a character [[restrained]] in place: [[bound_wrists]], [[fixed_restraints]], [[handcuffs]], etc. The restraints can be on a character, or it can be implied that they will be used to restrain a character.

Characters that are [[held_down]] [i]are[/i] restrained, but they are not considered in [b]restraints[/b]. Likewise, characters that are stuck may be restrained in their movements, but unless they were purposefully stuck there, they aren't in restraints.

title: operation_flashpoint
body:
A combat simulator series, started by Bohemia Interactive Studios with [b]Operation Flashpoint: Cold War Crisis[/b] in 2001, re-released as [i]ARMA: Cold War Assault[/i] in 2011.

Set in 1985, it involves a war between the US and the USSR on a group of islands.

Its realism led to special military versions released for real militaries, such as the United States Marine Corps. 

The original games made by Bohemia Interactive would see a spiritual successor from the same developer in the form of the [[arma_(series)|ARMA]] series starting from 2006 onwards.

The intellectual property of the series would be retained by the original game's publisher, Codemasters, who would go on to develop and release their own sequel, [[Operation Flashpoint: Dragon Rising]], in 2009.

title: p1y_ginga
body:
The [b]Yokosuka P1Y [i]Ginga[/i][/b] (銀河, "Galaxy") was built to a requirement by the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] Air Service for a replacement to the [[G4M]] medium bomber, and as such it was intended to have a bomb carrying capacity of 2,000 lb (907kg), be just as fast as the [[A6M Zero]] and possess the ability to dive bomb as well as drop torpedoes.

It was equipped with the mighty Nakajima Homare engines, which propelled it to much higher speeds than its predecessors when coupled with its efficient, aerodynamic design. However, such refinement meant that the aircraft was extremely hard to service, tricky to manufacture, and expensive; as such, only around a thousand P1Ys were introduced into service, with most of them being the P1Y1 dive/torpedo bomber variant, and a very small number of P1Y2-S [I]Kyokko[/i] (極光, "Aurora") night fighters powered by Kasei engines, which proved to be insufficient and were mostly converted back into bombers.

title: ran_straherz
body:
An [[original]] character by [[Rakurakutei Ramen]]. Originally the vengeful spirit of a brutally raped and murdered girl, she was defeated by [[Kamishiro Seren]] and imprisoned in a "[[jack-o'-lantern|Jack o' Ran-tan]]" to get over her grudge. Eventually, she returned to her former form of a young girl with [[long_hair|long]] [[purple hair]], two "ears" of which are held up by white [[bow]]s. Due to half of her body never being found after the murder, her lower body is ethereal, and can transform into a Jack-o'-Lantern to dispense chocolates, candies, and other treats.

Ran is often seen with [[Ujikintoki Tamaryu]] and [[Kagurazaki Shizuki]]. She's very quiet and withdrawn compared to the others, often replying shyly or fiddling to appear busy if not clasping her hands to her chest. This, however, doesn't tend to prevent her getting drawn into the other character's goofy antics.

Until the aftermath of [i]Ghostrick Live[/i], she was the only character with a consistently different speech bubble style, with semi-transparent bubbles and a rounded gothic font.

In [i]Ghostrick Live[/i], [spoiler]she is revealed to be an artificial ghost, a duplicate of a certain Etranger Shutulia that gained self-awareness and an individual personality thanks to Seren, her friends and the rest of the cast. She would eventually become whole and gain life, becoming a living ghost in the process thanks to having merged with other Etranger copies. The merging process also produced a duplicate of Ran, essentially an identical twin with a copy of her memories but with a rapidly diverging personality. She would be dubbed Ren.[/spoiler]

title: guanyin
body:
[b]Guanyin[/b] or [b]Guan Yin[/b] (/ˌɡwɑːnˈjɪn/) is the most commonly used Chinese translation of the bodhisattva known as [b]Avalokiteśvara.[/b] In English usage, Guanyin refers to the Buddhist bodhisattva associated with compassion and venerated chiefly by followers of Mahayana Buddhist schools as practiced in the sinosphere.

The Lotus Sutra describes Avalokiteśvara as a bodhisattva who can take the form of any type of God including Indra or Brahma; any type of Buddha, any type of King or Chakravartin or even any kind of Heavenly Guardian including Vajrapani and Vaisravana as well as any gender male or female, adult or child, human or non-human being, in order to teach the Dharma to sentient beings. Folk traditions in China and other East Asian countries have added many distinctive characteristics and legends to Guanyin c.q. Avalokiteśvara. Avalokiteśvara was originally depicted as a male bodhisattva, and therefore wears chest-revealing clothing and may even sport a light moustache. Although this depiction still exists in the Far East, Guanyin is more often depicted as a woman in modern times. Additionally, some people believe that Guanyin is androgynous or perhaps without gender.

title: robert_patrick
body:
[b]Robert Hammond Patrick Jr.[/b] (born November 5, 1958) is an American actor. Best known for his portrayals of various villainous characters, Patrick is a Saturn Award winner with four nominations.

Patrick dropped out of college when drama class sparked his interest in acting, and entered film in 1986. After playing a supporting role in [[Die Hard]] 2 (1990), Patrick starred as the [[T-1000]], the main antagonist of [[Terminator 2: Judgment Day]] (1991)—a role he reprised for cameo appearances in Wayne's World (1992) and Last Action Hero (1993). Other film credits include Fire in the Sky (1993), Striptease (1996), Cop Land (1997), The Faculty (1998), Spy Kids (2001), Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle (2003), Ladder 49 (2004), Walk the Line (2005), Flags of Our Fathers (2006), We Are Marshall (2006), Bridge to Terabithia (2007), The Men Who Stare at Goats (2009), and Safe House (2012).

In television, Patrick is known for his portrayals of FBI Special Agent John Doggett in [[The X-Files]] and Colonel Tom Ryan in The Unit, and has played ongoing roles in series such as The Outer Limits, The Sopranos, Elvis, [[Avatar: The Last Airbender]], Burn Notice, Last Resort, Sons of Anarchy and From Dusk Till Dawn: The Series. In 2014 he was cast in the role of DHS agent Cabe Gallo in the CBS drama series Scorpion. He was also guest host on season two of GunnyTime.

[i]NouCome[/i], English: [i]My Mental Choices Are Completely Interfering With My School Romantic Comedy[/i]) is a light novel series illustrated by [[Yukiwo]]. It has since been adapted into a 10 episode anime that began airing in Fall 2013 on Oct. 10.

The show revolves around the main character [[Amakusa Kanade]], a high school student who has a series of "Absolute Choices" that appear before him due to a curse. These choices are almost always bizarre, sadistic or more simply cruel and refusing to act on any of them will result in a powerful headache until a choice is met. title: a.r.e.s.
body: [i][b]A.R.E.S.: Extinction Agenda[/b][/i] is a run-and-gun platforming game by the Thailand-based Extend Studios and published by ORiGO Games. It was a runner-up on Microsoft's Dream.Build.Play contest of 2010. The game centers around the titular Ares, a combat robot developed to fight mutated robots infected with a mysterious gas known as "Zytron" while investigating a derelict space station. The game is noted being for borrowing gameplay elements from [i]Abuse[/i] and [i][[Metroid]][/i] with a rock-inspired soundtrack by HyperDuck Studios. It was remade in 2013 for the Xbox 360 and re-released on PC in 2014 as [i]A.R.E.S.: Extinction Agenda EX[/i], featuring streamlined gameplay elements, new content, and an extra playable character.

title: shimura_takako
body:
Artist and author of several manga series, including [[aoi_hana|Aoi Hana]] and [[hourou_musuko|Hourou Musuko]]. Born 1973, female. Japanese name: 志村貴子.

Shimura's works often address topics related to sexual minorities. Her storytelling incorporates realistic, romantic, and sometimes erotic elements with nonlinear narrative techniques into a soft slice-of-life style targeted towards both male and female readers.

Her art style is soft as well, and clear and simple to the point of sometimes getting critique for being vague. She has herself admitted having difficulty with designing characters specific enough. In addition to the  usual monochrome manga illustrations, she also produces colored works; her [[watercolor_(medium)|watercolor]] ones (e.g. post #363057) deserve special mention.

title: shadow_sword_(fire_emblem)
body:
The Shadow Sword (
あんこくの剣
lit. Darkness Sword) is a cursed Sword that appears exclusively in Fire Emblem Gaiden and Fire Emblem: Thracia 776. In the latter game, this sword is passed into Mareeta's hands by Raydrik, where the corrupted sword essentially takes control of her mind, compelling her to attack anyone at sight, be they friend or foe. The curse is later purged by Saias, whereupon the now-neutralised blade is returned to Mareeta, functioning as a unique weapon that is bound exclusively to her.

title: revolver_fanning
body:
A shooting technique for single-action [[revolver|revolvers]] in which one holds down the trigger in one hand, and uses the other to hit the hammer singularly or repeatedly without any part of the cocking hand remaining in contact with the revolver or support hand. This rotates the cylinder and fires the weapon, allowing for rapid fire. 

Popularized by western films, it is widely considered to be inadvisable for use in real-life firefights, as it provides no tactical benefit to speak of.

title: great_wall_of_china
body: [b]The Great Wall of China[/b] (Chinese: [i]萬里長城[/i]; pinyin: Wanli Changcheng) is the collective name of a series of fortification systems generally built across the historical northern borders of [[China]] to protect and consolidate territories of Chinese states and empires against various nomadic groups of the steppe and their polities. Several walls were being built from as early as the 7th century BC by ancient Chinese states; they were later joined together by [[Qin Shi Huang]] , the first Emperor of China.
